WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.840
Welcome back, this week we're teaching the horses to receive a reward in the

00:29.840 --> 00:35.880
form of a pet. So we're using the exercise of using an obstacle or a jump,

00:35.880 --> 00:41.400
a cavaletti or a pole, having the horse go over the poles or cavalettis and then

00:41.400 --> 00:48.640
stopping and giving them a pat. In this example here I've got three cavalettis

00:48.640 --> 00:54.000
set on nine feet apart so that we can do this in walk, trot and canter. In this

00:54.000 --> 00:58.720
particular horse's demonstration we'll do it in the walk and the trot. So as you

00:58.720 --> 01:03.960
can see the start is to lead him over the cavalettis and show him exactly how

01:03.960 --> 01:10.240
to go over the cavalettis and then when I stop my feet he must stop his feet and

01:10.240 --> 01:15.420
you see me there correcting him exactly where I stopped he needs to stop. After

01:15.420 --> 01:21.400
that point he gets a pet. So they should be so in tune that they could stop at

01:21.400 --> 01:27.080
any time and they're comfortable being over top of the pole and clearing the

01:27.080 --> 01:33.000
pole and knowing exactly where it is. So you see there this horse actually really

01:33.000 --> 01:38.400
likes being scratched so I'm adding that to the reward, a pet on the forehead, a

01:38.400 --> 01:44.560
little scratch on the neck. If your horse doesn't like being scratched avoid that.

01:45.280 --> 01:51.320
So watch out for things and be aware of some things, how accurate is your

01:51.320 --> 01:56.800
horse at knowing their own body and being able to manipulate it over the

01:56.800 --> 02:02.640
obstacles. This tells you a lot about how your horse learns and how they move

02:02.640 --> 02:07.600
their body and how they receive information from obstacles and outside

02:07.600 --> 02:10.120
sources.

02:14.080 --> 02:19.200
So the next stage is to have them go over the obstacles alone without your

02:19.200 --> 02:24.920
lead and you see here he's very comfortable doing that and he can stop

02:24.920 --> 02:31.760
when I stop. If your horse is nervous they're gonna want to come towards you

02:31.760 --> 02:36.880
and not do it on their own, simply encourage them to step away from you and

02:36.880 --> 02:44.000
do the obstacle or solve the problem on their own. Remember every groundwork

02:44.000 --> 02:48.840
exercise we do, every exercise we do with the horses is to direct the horse to

02:48.840 --> 02:54.280
control himself, not so that we can control the horses. The more the horse is

02:54.280 --> 02:59.280
confident with his own self-control the more confident he will be with the task

02:59.280 --> 03:09.000
that we give him. Good, so now we've moved on to encouraging the trot. You can tell

03:09.000 --> 03:12.760
this horse is not paying attention so I'm having to give him reminders on how

03:12.760 --> 03:21.640
to pay attention, come in and get his reward. So if your horse is slightly

03:21.640 --> 03:27.680
distracted like this one you may have to indicate to them exactly where they

03:27.680 --> 03:32.160
should be, whether they should be solving the problem, coming for the reward or

03:32.160 --> 03:39.240
simply resting. So you see I'm giving him the little trot steps with my feet to

03:39.240 --> 03:44.960
encourage him to trot and then I'm also having to remind him how to halt

03:44.960 --> 03:51.760
because his attention level is low. If your horse is more sensitive you're

03:51.760 --> 03:57.640
gonna want to be very very light and effective with your voice, your body

03:57.640 --> 04:02.560
commands and make sure that you're not misfiring any commands towards them so

04:02.560 --> 04:06.960
that they stay light and sensitive to your aids.

04:11.760 --> 04:19.320
When repeating this exercise repeat it until it's so boring for the horses,

04:19.320 --> 04:24.760
repeat it until they could do it in their sleep, do it so many times and

04:24.760 --> 04:31.920
recognize the equality of doing it both left and right exactly the same, exactly

04:31.960 --> 04:37.320
the same amount of times and there's gonna be a harder side for the horse. You

04:37.320 --> 04:40.640
might have to practice that a little bit more but recognize that you want to make

04:40.640 --> 04:49.200
it even in the end. Here we have another example of a horse that's very confident

04:49.200 --> 04:53.880
with their ability to maneuver their own body. This is a young horse still the same

04:53.880 --> 04:59.520
age but this horse is more confident, more aware of their body so we can use

04:59.520 --> 05:05.400
this same concept over a larger jump like this little barrel here that's

05:05.400 --> 05:10.840
about two feet high. So he's already at the stage where he can jump it on his

05:10.840 --> 05:17.160
own. Same as the other horse, this one needs a reminder to pay attention and

05:17.160 --> 05:21.360
make sure that he's on task in the moment that he needs to be doing what he

05:21.360 --> 05:25.520
needs to be doing. So jumping, he's jumping, coming back and getting a pet,

05:25.640 --> 05:30.600
he's coming back and getting a pet. You see this horse is distracted by maybe

05:30.600 --> 05:36.360
the other areas of the arena. Do your best to ignore that part and keep focused

05:36.360 --> 05:42.680
on the task that you're asking him to do and the horses will respond by paying

05:42.680 --> 05:46.480
attention to that task as well.

